04941nam a22007095i 9780824837983DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20132013hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248379837 a10.1515/97808248379832doi  a(DE-B1597)483943  a(OCoLC)1024055515  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0240002bisacsh04a294.365709512492231 aYü, Chün-fang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPassing the Light :bThe Incense Light Community and Buddhist Nuns in Contemporary Taiwan /cChün-fang Yü; ed. by George J. Tanabe. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in Contemporary Buddhism ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: Why Study Nuns? -- t2. The Beginning of the Incense Light Community -- t3. Wuyin, the Guiding Light of the Community -- t4. College Buddhist Studies Societies -- t5. Incense Light Buddhist Seminary for Nuns -- t6. Buddhist Adult Classes -- t7. Profiles of Individual Nuns -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe term “revival” has been used to describe the resurgent vitality of Buddhism in Taiwan. Particularly impressive is the quality and size of the nun’s order: Taiwanese nuns today are highly educated and greatly outnumber monks. Both characteristics are unprecedented in the history of Chinese Buddhism and are evident in the Incense Light community (Xiangguang). Passing the Light is the first in-depth case study of the community, which was founded in 1974 and remains a small but influential order of highly educated nuns who dedicate themselves to teaching Buddhism to lay adults.The work begins with a historical survey of Buddhist nuns in China, based primarily on the sixth-century biographical collection Lives of the Nuns and stories of nuns in subsequent centuries. This is followed by discussions on the early history of the Incense Light community; the life of Wuyin, one of its most prominent leaders; and the crucial role played by Buddhist studies societies on college campuses, where many nuns were first introduced to Incense Light. Later chapters look at the curriculum and innovative teaching methods at the Incense Light seminary and the nuns’ efforts to teach Buddhism to adults. The work ends with portraits of individual nuns, providing details on their backgrounds, motivations for becoming nuns, and the problems or setbacks they have encountered both within and without the Incense Light community.This engaging study enriches the literature on the history of Buddhist nuns, seminaries, and education, and will find an appreciative audience among scholars and students of Chinese religion, especially Buddhism, as well as those interested in questions of religion and modernity and women and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious orders for womenzTaiwan. 0aBuddhist nunszTaiwan. 0aBuddhist sanghaszTaiwan. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aTanabe, George J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483798340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824837983423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824837983.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec200